Setting up Mahogany, its configuration files
\layout Subsection

User configuration files
\layout Standard

When run for the first time, Mahogany creates a directory called 
\family typewriter 
.M
\family default 
 in the user's home directory.
 The file 
\family typewriter 
$HOME/.M/config
\family default 
 will contain the current program configuration for this user.
 Only values different from the default configuration are stored here.
 If you want to obtain a list of all possible options, you can manually
 add the entry
\layout Quote


\family typewriter 
RecordDefaults = 1
\layout Standard

to the 
\family typewriter 
[M/Profiles]
\family default 
 section of the configuration file.
 This will cause all values which are used to be written to the configuration
 file.
\layout Subsection

System wide configuration file
\layout Standard

Mahogany can be pre-configured on a system wide basis by supplying a 
\family typewriter 
M.conf
\family default 
 file in the Mahogany installation directory (e.g.
 
\family typewriter 
/usr/share/Mahogany/M.conf
\family default 
).
 The syntax for this configuration file is identical to the user's configuration
 file, so you can just copy a user's file to this location and edit it by
 hand.
 Useful settings for a system wide default are servers or mail return addresses.
 Note though, that Mahogany will not run properly as 
\family typewriter 
root
\family default 
.
 Entries prefixed with an exclamation mark 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 are marked as immutable and cannot be overwritten by the user.
 This can be used by the system administrator to hard-wire certain settings,
 like, for example the return mail addresses or mail servers to use.
